{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_junco_ver01/data/sn83045499/0039334216A/1946043001/0823.xml":{"full_text":"THE DAILY ALASKA EMPIRE\n\u201cALL THE NEWS ALL THE TIME\u201d\nVOL. LXVI., NO. 10,258\nJUNEAU, ALASKA, TUESDAY, APRIL 30, 1946\nMEMBER ASSOCIATED PRESS\nPRICE TEN CENTS\nKILL MAC ARTHUR\nFOUR-POWER\nPEACE PACT\nIS PROPOSED\nPermanent German Dis\narmament Is Planned\nAlert Kept on Japan\nPARIS, April 30.\u2014A long-term\nUnited States foreign policy, pledg\ning American military might to I\nkeep the peace in Germany for at i\nleast a quarter of a century, emerg\ned today in the form of a proposal\nby U. S. Secretary of State James\nF. Byrnes for a four-power mutual\nassistance pact.\nThe hitherto secret United States\nproposal, which would combine the\nmilitary forces of the United\nStates, Russia, Britain and France,\nto assure a permanent German\ndisarmament, was made public byj\nByrnes at a press conference last\nnight following a five-hour session\nof the foreign ministers' confer\nence.\nAnother Alert\nThe Secretary of State also dis\nclosed he had drafted a similar pact\nto keep United States and other\nAllied forces on the alert against\na revival of militarism in Japan,\nbut declined to reveal details of this\nproposal.\nByrnes says Premier Stalin had\nsupported the idea for the four\npower treaty on Germany when the\ntwo discussed the matter in Mos\ncow last Christmas. However, Mo\nlotov, Russian Foreign Minister, yes\nterday opposed placing the matter\non the conference agenda in con\nnection with general discussions\non Germany.\nFrance and Britain have accepted\nthe proposal in principle, Byrnes\nsaid, and Russia has expressed\nwillingness to discuss it. although\nwithout setting a definite time, j\nMay Go On Agenda\nWhether the treaty draft will be\nplaced on the agenda remained un\nsettled when Byrnes asked for ad\njournment of the conference last\nnight.\nThe proposal requires German ac\nceptance as a condition for thej\nwithdrawal of Allied occupational\nforces from the Reich, and pro\nvides for four-power supervision of\nGermany for at least 25 years af\nter the end of the present occu\npation.\nl^yrnes\u2019 suggestion would insure\nthat German armed forces are\n\u201ccompletely disarmed, demobilized\nfind disbanded;\" that such organi\nzations as the storm troopers and\ngestapo are wiped out, and that no\nmilitary equipment or explosives\nare manufactured.\nThe Washington\nMerry Go Round\nBy DREW PEARSON\nWASHINGTON Ten Senators\u2014\nboth Democrats and Republicans\u2014\ngot together secretly the other day\nto study that most sacred of all\nsacred cows\u2014Senate rules. Behind\ntheir meeting was the conviction\nthat die-hard Dixie Democrats can\nblock any measure they oppose via\nthe filibuster, and that the major\nity must rule if democracy is to\nfunction in the USA.\nThe secret meeting took place\nafter senators received a flood of\nletters both for and against the\nattempt by Wayne Morse, Oregon\nRepublican to secure passage of\nthe Anti-Poll Tax Bill through\nunanimous consent of the Senate.\nOnly Senators on the floor at the\ntime Morse attempted this strategy\nwere Morse himself and Republican\nWilliam Langer of North Dakota.\nLiberal Democrat Warren Mag\nnuson of Seattle, Wash., was pre\nsiding. Had he immediately asked\nSenators if there was objection,\nthere would have been none and\nthe Anti-Poll Tax Bill would have\npassed. Morse had identified the\nBill only by number, so Magnuson\ndid not at once recognize it. But,\neven if he had, probably he would\nhave hesitated to pass a contro\nversial bill without debate.\nHe was rescued from this dilem\nma by Senator Ernest MacParland,\nArizona Democrat, who quickly\ncame to the floor and objected.\nSince then. Senate mail has been\n/Continued on Page Four)\nSLOW VOTE\nIS POLLED\nIN PRIMARY\nVote at 3 o'clock This\nAfternoon, 317 Demo\ncrats, 145 Republicans\nAt 3 o\u2019clock this afternoon only\n317 Democrats and 145 Republicans\nhad cast their ballots in today\u2019s\nTerritorial primary at the three\npolling places in Juneau and with\nfavorable weather that should\ncause a large vote.\nThe vote at 3 o\u2019clock was as fol- j\nlows:\nPrecinct No. 1\u2014116 Democrats;\n70 Republicans, voting slow.\nPrecinct No. 2\u2014109 Democrats;\n48 Republicans, voting slow.\nPrecinct No. 3\u201492 Democrats; 27\nRepublicans, voting slow.\nThe polls close tonight at 7\no\u2019clock. Qualifications are resident\nof Territory for one year and pre\ncinct 111 which vote is cast, 30 days.\nNo previous registration is requir\ned.\nAt 3 o'clock on the afternoon of\nApril 25. 1944, the last Territorial\nPrimary, the following was the vote\nat the Juneau precincts:\nNo. 1\u2014288 Democrats; 65 Re\npublicans.\nNo 2\u2014143 Democrats; 14 Republi- j\ncans.\nNo. 3\u2014120 Democrats; 23 Repub\nlicans. j\nDON O'CONNOR\nIS IN JUNEAU l\nON RATE CASE\nDonald J. O'Connor, Price Exe\ncutive for Office of Price Admin-\nMiration's Ninth Region (which in\ncludes Alaska and all other U. S.\nTerritories), today said OPA will\nrecommend freight rate increases j\namounting to only a small fraction I\nof those demanded by the steam\nship companies when rate hearings\nreopen in Washington, D. C., May\n22.\u2022\nO'Connor, economist associated I\nwith the Juneau OPA office from\nApril, 1943, until January, 1946,.\nwhen he received a promotion and\ntransfer to Washington, D. C., ar-!\nrived Sunday on official business j\nend will leave at the end of the j\nweek. His wife and two sons, who\nhave lived in Juneau since O\u2019Con\nner's transfer, will follow him to\nI the States in another week to take\nup residence in Syracuse, N. Y.,\npending an apartment vacancy in\nihe Capitol City.\nOPA will piesent the following\npoints at the new hearings, O\u2019Con- j\nnor said:\n(li Snow the effect of the pre\nsent and proposed rates on the1\ncost of living and conducting busi\ni ness in Alaska.\n<2> Forecast the level of antici\npated business activity in the Ter\nritory in 1946-47. (He said he be\nlieves the strikes already l^ve im\npaired the 1946 economy but that\nthe business outlook for 1947 is\ni \u201cpromising\u201d with many new enter\ni prises to be expected here.\nj (31 Estimate steamship traffic\n\u2022for 1946-47.\nJ (4) Call the Maritime Commis\nsion\u2019s attention to the \u201cremarkably\nexpensive operation resulting from\nthe purchase of ancient ships.\u201d\nj O'Connor pointed out that the con\nsumer (traveller and importer) has\nto pay lor service on the basis of\nj the most expensively-maintained\nships in the world.\nf, In conclusion OPA will recom\nj mend \"certain rate increases which\nin OPA s judgement will be least\ndisturbing to the cost of living and\nenterprise in Alaska; but none of\nthe recommended increases, will\nhave any serious effect on Alaska's\neconomy,\u201d O'Connor added.\nHe also stated that the $10,000,\n000 deficit claimed by the company\n\u201cis so far away that OPA is unable\nto give it any serious attention.\u201d\nWorking with O\u2019Connor in Wash\nington are Price Specialist Flor\nence Kemp, also formerly associat\ni ed with the Juneau office, and\nWallace Lind, recently transferred\nfrom the Anchorage office. Lind is\nQPA's Alaska specialist, O\u2019Connor\nsaid.\nPapua is a name for the island\n;of New buinea.\nTurn Heat On\nBlack Market\nIn Food Fight\nDouble Aim Is Announced\nby Government-De\nvelopments Made\nWASHINGTON. April 30. The\ngovernment turned more heat on\nthe blade market today with the i\ndouble aim of improving the do\nmestic food situation and halting\nthe diversion of famine relief sup- i\nplies for overseas.\nThe Justice Department an\nnounced the start of a \"vigorous\ncrackdown\" on income tax evaders\nsuspected of reaping huge black\nmarket profits.\nThe broad food picture was\nmarked by these developments: i\n1. \u2014The Agriculture Department)\nreported that it will take five years\nto restore European food production\nto pre-war levels.\n2. \u2014Another agriculture report\nplaced the nation\u2019s April corn sup\nply stocks 19 percent under last\nyear's figures.\n3. \u2014Secretary Anderson warned\nthat food shortages here may con\ntinue into 1948 and asserted in a\nspeech that further food sacrifices\nwill be sought from the people.\n4. \u2014Latest government statistics\ndisclosed that the general level of)\nfarm product prices soared this\nmonth to their highest mark since\nJuly 1920. The lift came from ma\njor advances in prices for meat an\nimals, fruits and cotton.\nDAYLIGHT SAVING\nON PACIFIC COAST\nNOT DECIDED YET\n_\nI BY THE ASSOCIATED PRESS)\nThe question or whether daylight\nsaving time shall be inaugurated\nin the Pacific Northwest is still j\npretty much undecided this morn\ning. Governor Snell said in Port-'\nland last night that he is con\nvinccd after talking with Governor\nWallgren of Washington that if j\nCalifornia and Washington move I\ntiie clock ahei d an hour, Oregon\nshould follow suit. He declared that:\nhe and Wallgren agree that day\nlight saving should be adopted on j\na coastwise basis, if at all.\nIn Yakima, Wallgren announces i\nthat he\u2019ll confer again with Sneil\nThursday before announcing a de- i\ncision for his state.\nRedin Trial Date\nSet for June 25, j\nJudge Indicates;\nSEATTLE, April 30\u2014 Federal\nJudge Lloyd Black notified counsel\ntoday that on May 16, they might:\nexpect him to set 10 a. m., June 25\nas the time for starting the espion- j\nage trial of Nicolai G. Redin, Rus- i\nsian naval lieutenant. He said he;\nwould not set the trial date now\nas defense attorneys had indicated,\nthey would file some motions for1\nhearing May 15.\nThe defense had asked for an\nAugust date and the District At\nterney had wanted it. set for the\nfirst week in June.\nHerbert Hoover Is in\nShanghai; To Report\nOn Food Situation\nI SHANGHAI, April 30\u2014Herbert\nI Hoover Has arrived here by plane\ntrom Manila\u2014 weary from his\n1 round-the-world study of food con\nditions'.\nHoover is expected to spend four\nor five days in China and to visit\nthe capital\u2014Narfking.\nThe former United States Presi\ndent immediately conferred today\nwith authorities about the food\nsituation in Cnina, which is facing\nits worst famine in many years.\nHoover is expected to go to Japan\nand Ko-ea before returning to\nWashington to report to President\nTruman.\nHITLER PACT\nWITH SPAIN\nIS REVEALED\nSoviet Press Publishes\nDocuments Confirming\nSecret Alliance\nMOSCOW. April 30.\u2014The Soviet\npress published today pholostatic\ncopies of documents which it said\nconfirmed the signing of a secret\nmilitary alliance between Hitler\nand Franco Spain in Madrid on\nFebruary 12, 1943.\nThe Russian news agency, Tass,\nsaid the documents were discovered\nby Red Army intelligence officers\nin the archives of the German\nforeign ministry during the battle\nfor Berlin.\nThe Moscow radio broadcast full\ndetails, including texts.\nThe broadcast said the docu\nments showed that when General\nissimo Francisco Franco formulat\ned the nlliance with Hitler he \u201cun\ndertook; at the appropriate moment'\nto come out against the Allied\narmies.\"\nThese documents show, the broad\ncast said, \u201cThat Hitler's accom\nplice, Franco, not only in fact as\nsisted Hitlerite Germany in the\nwar against the Allies, but on Feb.\n12, 1943, formulated de jure his\nmilitary alliance with Hitler and\nundertook at the appropriate mo\nment to come out against the Allied\narmies.\"\nThe broadcast followed by only\na few hours a decision by the Uni\nted Nations Security Council, with\nRussia\u2019s delegate abstaining, to as\nsign to a subcommittee the investi\ngation of Poland\u2019s charges that\nSpain is a threat to world peace.\nU.S. PLANE\nIS BUZZED\nBY RUSS\nVIENNA, April 30.\u2014Two Russian\nfighters buzzed the personal plane\nof Gen. Mark W. Clark today as\nit was being flown from Vienna to\nLinz by Brig. Gen. Ralph A. Snave\nly, commandev of the U.S.F.A. Air\nDivision.\nThis was the third incident in\nvolving Soviet fighters and Ameri\ncan planes in 10 days.\nClark was not aboard his plane, a\nB-17 Flying Fortress. Clark made\nhis third protest against the Rus\nsian activities when he learned of\ntoday\u2019s attack.\nThe Russian fighters made speed\nruns toward the B-17 several times\nbut fired no shots such as marked\nthe act involving two U. S. trans\nport planes previously.\nThe radioman aboard the B-17\nreported the details as the plane\ncontinued its flight.\nThe B-17 left the airport outside\nVienna at 9:50 a. m. and it was\nabout 25 minutes later when the\nSoviet planes approached.\nDeath Toll in\nLuzon Election\nReported at 28\ni MANILA, April 30.\u2014A dispatch\nto the Manila Bulletin says that\ni 17 more persons have been killed\nI in Central Luzon. This raises to\n138 the number slain in violence re\ni suiting from the Philippine elec\n\u25a0tion last week. In the latest out\nbreak. 15 guerrilla supporters of\nI President Manuel Osmena and two\nmilitary police are said to have\nbeen slain in battles' in two Cen\ntral Luzon Provinces.\nAlaska Juneau Mine.\nReport for '45 Made\nSAN FRANCISCO, April 30\u2014Al\naska Juneau bold Mining Company\nreports a $103,643 net loss for 1945,\ncompved with $280,180 loss for\n1944. President C. A. Norris sat;\nhe coulck not predict when mining\noperations would be resumed, la\nbor and material shortages having\nchanged little;\nMENACE OF\nSPAIN TO\nBE PROBED\n\nSubcommittee ofUNSC Be\ngins Investigation in\nSecret Move\nNEW YORK, April 30\u2014The first\nI investigating subcommittee of the\nUnited-Nations Security Council be\ngan compiling evidence in secrecy\ntoday to determine whether Franco\nSpain menaces the peace as charg\ned by Poland.\nIp the first phase of an inquiry\nauthorized yesterday by a resolu\ntion stamping the council's \u201cun-;\nanimous moral condemnation\u201d on\nthe Franco regime, the subcommit-1\ntee disclosed it was committed to\nkeep certain submitted documents\nconfidential.\nThe subcommittee called first for\ndata on Spain now in the hands\nof the various United Nations. This\nwill be supplemented -by other evi-\ndence. including that of ^panish\nRepublican leaders exiled in Paris.\nVery Confidential\nThe investigators did not disclose\nthe sources of documents on Spain\nwhich are classed as too confiden\ntial to be aired in public now,1\nand there was no indication that\nSpain herself would offer any in\nformation.\nAs it began its inquiries, how\never. the subcommittee was con\nfronted with the probability that\nnew evidence would be fed to it\nlrom both Russia and the Spanish\nRe pelicans.\nThe exiled Spanish Republicans,\nwho are represented here by two\nobservers Fernando de Los Rios\nand Jose Antonio Aguirre indi- i\ncated that Prime Minister Joe Gi\nral of the exile regime was ex\npected to arrive here from Paris at\nany moment with nqw information.\nJust An Insult\nMADRID, April 30.\u2014The Fa-j\nlange newspaper Arriba asserted to- j\nday that the United Nations' Secur- j\nity Council decision to investigate\nSpain was \"an insult we shall for\nget with difficulty.\"\nMOREMINERS\nTO BE CALLED\nOUT BY LEWIS\nWASHINGTON, April 30.\u2014John\nL. Lewis today notified the govern\nment he would call out 75,000\nPennsylvania anthracite miners in\n30 days to back up contract de\nmands similar to those which have\nshut dov/n the soft coal mines.\nLewis informed the Wage Sta\nbilization Board that anthracite\ncontract negotiations would begin\nFriday, May 10, and that notice of\ndispute was being transmitted \u201cin\norder to protect cur membership\nunder the terms of the War Labor\nDisputes Act.\"\nSimultaneously, Paul W. Duller,\ni special government conciliator as\nsigned to the soft coal negotiations,\nannounced his resignation from\n1 government service in protest\nagainst the government's method of\nhandling the case.\nFuller told reporters of his de\nrision as he left the office of Sec\nretary r.f Labor Schwellenbach.\nFIVE MEAT PLANTS\nBACK TO\nOWNERSBY 60VT.\nWASHINGTON. April 30. The\ngovernment restored the plants of\nthe five big meat packers to the\nowners today.\nThe facilities were seized Janu\nary 26 when i. strike of APL and\nCIO packing house workers threat\nened serious curtailment of meat\nsupplies\nThe White House announced all\nexcept five stockyards were turned\nback to Armour, Swift, Wilson,\nCudahy and Morrell.\nThere aie approximately 7,083\nIslands in the Philippines.\nTURNED\nCannery Workers' Strike\nMay Come to End Tonight;\nProposals Accepted, Report\nAMMUNITION\nBLOWS UP AT\nJERSEY PIER\nU. S. S. Destroyer Escort\nSolar Demolished\nin Explosion\nEARLE, N. J\u201e April 30.\u2014The des\ntroyer escort U. S. S. Solar was\nvirtually demolished today by three\nexplosions which destroyed an am\nmunition warehouse and blew a\nhuge gaping hole in an Earle naval\ndepot loading pier on lower New\nYork Bay.\nA Navy spokesman here said one\nofficer and seven enlisted men\nwere reported missing, but there\nare no known dead. The spokes\nman estimated 80 were injured,\nmost of them suffering minor burns,\nbut explained the casualty list was\nnot complete.\nThe Solar, which was described\nas a \u201ccomplete loss,\u201d was taking\nwater late this afternoon and list\ning, but was buoyed up partially by\nhalters.\nEight sailors, who laapsd into th*\nwater when the first blast occurred,\nwere rescued. A railroad car, load\ned with ammunition, was blown up.1\nResultant fire on the ship and\npier was extinguished after an\nhour's battle.\nThe ship blew up as ammunition\nwas being unloaded.\nThe Third Naval District head\nquarters in New York said most\npersonnel got clear after an ini-,\ntial blast, which was moderate. A\nsecond explosion, the Naval Dis\ntrict spokesman said, was of major\nviolence and demolished a lighter\nacross the pier which extends out\n2 1-2 miles into the bay.\nCARRIER TASK\nFORCE MAY BE\nSENT, ALASKAj\nSAN DIECO, Calif., April 30\nU. S. Fifth Fleet maneuvers along\nthe Pacific Coast this year may\ninclude a Carrier task force to the\nAleutians for a summer cruise prior\nto the major operation set for No\nvember or December, Vice Adm.\nFrederick C. Sherman, fleet com\nmander, said her* today.\nThe plans are conditioned, how\never, he told a news conferenc e, on\nthe availability of ships and per\nsonnel. Fall maneuver plans call\nfor amphibious invasion of Mqn\nterey, Calif., or San Clemente Is-!\nland.\nUSS Pennsylvania\nOff for Dote with\nBikini Atom Bomb\nLOS ANGELES, April 30.\u2014The\nbattleship Pennsylvania, one-time\n1 flagship of the U. S. Fleet, steam\nI cd out of the harbor yesterday for\nher rendezvous with the atom bomb\ni at Bikini Atoll. She was the first\nicrf six men o\u2019war to leave this week\nfor the atom test.\nSTOCK QUOTATIONS\nNEW YORK, April 30\u2014 Closing\nquotation of Alaska Juneau mine\nstock today is 9, Alleghany Corpor\nation 6'i, American 96'i. Anaconda\n48, Commonwealth and Southern\nI 4, Curtiss-Wright 7t*, International\nHarvester 94\u20184. Kennecott 60, New\nYork Central 26 Ti, Northern Pacific\n30*i, United Corporation 5*4, U. S,\nSteel 83 Ti, Pound *4.031 a.\nI Sales today were 1,000,000 shares,\nj Dow, Jones average* today are\n'as follows: industrials 206.77, rails\n64.17, utilities 43.34.\nNegotiations ending the present\ncannery workers' strike are expect\ned to be concluded satisfactorily\nby night fall, according to advices\nreceived up to noon today at Gov.\nGruening's office.\nA wire this morning from Fed\neral Conciliator A. L. Peterson at\nKetchikan, and addressed to the\nGovernor, read as follows: \u201cSalmon\nIndustry accepted proposal last\nnight. Union will vote on ac\nceptance today.\"\nJust before noon, Gov. Grueningj\ntalked with Peterson over the radio\nphone concerning the situation and\nwas assured that \"apparently the\nstrike will be settled by tonight.\u201d j\nConfident that the Union would!\nvote favorably on the issue, Pet-1\nerson planned to leave Ketchikan\nthis afternoon by plane for Seattle.!\nESPIONAGE LAWS\nHAVE APPARENT\nWEAKNESS, CLAIM!\nWASHINGTON, April 30.\u2014Sena-1\ntor Eastland (D-Miss) said today:\ntliere is an \u201capparent weakness\u201d In j\nespionage laws whereby foreign gov- 1\nernments can obtain Information on\nsecret United States instruments of j\nwar. He made that statement to\nreporters after the first meeting of\na senate Judiciary subcommittee:\nconsidering a JjJH to prohibit sale\ntit Am*vican-made radar and elec-\ntronic equipment to foreigners.\nEastland said the situation ap- J\npeared to be such that foreign,\ngovernments by purchasing \u201cdc-1\nclassified\u201d (non-secret) parts and.\ncombining them through \u201cindustrial!\nknow-how\u201d can make \u201cclassified\u201d j\n(secret) apparatus.\nThe Senate Judiciary subcommit-|\ntee decided to bar the public and1\nreporters from its Initial hearing\ntoday on a proposal to prohibit sales\nof American-made radar and elec-1\ntronic equipment to foreigners j\nThe subcommittee took up the\nbill amid reports that Russia was\ninterested in buying such equip- j\nment. i\nSALVATION ARMY\nDRIVE ENDS HERE;\nIS SHORT OF GOAL\nThe Salvation Army Drive (or\nfunds to cover Salvationist work\nin Juneau for the next fiscal year\nclosed today approximately $800\nshort of its $4,600 goal.\nBrigadier C. O. Taylor said the\nyear's budget, already stripped to\nbare essentials would have to be\ndrafted and \"the cloth cut again\nto fit even a smaller man.\u201d\nKe thanked all Juneau residents1\nfor their contributions this year,\nand said he understood that the\ncampaign came at an unsettled and\ntrying time in the life of the\ncommunity.\ni Although there were more con\ntributions this year, many of them\nwere cut from 50 to 75 percent in\nsize, the Brigadier said.\nThere are still a number of\ni \u201ccall backs\" to hear from, he said.\n'A few late contiibutions were ex\npected to be received tomorrow.\nFIRE IS SET IN\ni ANCHORAGE JAIL;\nWOMEN PROTEST\nANCHORAGE, Alaska April 30.\u2014\nThe fire department, quartered In\nthe same building, squelched a\nblaze set In a bunk in the women\u2019s\nsection of the city jail yesterday.\nFifty women prisoners had sty\nthe fire as a protest against being\nconfined in the lockup where ac\n1 commcdalions for only 15 inmates\nwere available. Today the feminine\npopulation of the bastille remains\nat 50. The bunk total has dropped\nto 14.\n\nA. W. BRINDLK ARRIVES\nA. W. Brindle of Ketchikan has\narrived and is staying at the Bar*\nanof.\nU. 5. GENERAL\nIS MARKED\nFOR DEATH\nCommander Slated for As\nsassination on May\nDay in Tokyo\nTOKYO, April 30.\u2014General Mac\nArthur was marked for assassina\ntion May Day tomorrow with\nhand grenades and pistols \"some\ntime during Communistic demons\ntrations\" near his headquarters, his\noffice announced today.\nAmerican authorities learned of\nthe assassination plot through one\n\\of the participants whom Hideo\nTokayama, the accused Lut unap\nprehended leader, attempted to\npoison, said Brig. Gen. F. Baker,\nMacArthur's public relatione offi\ncer.\nThe Japanese government offi\ncially presented its apologies at\nMacArthur\u2019s office as reports of\nthe plot\u2014spreading like wildfire\nthrough Tokyo-stirred Japanese\nfears of harsher occupation poli\ncies.\nKyuchi Tokuda, general secretary\nof the Communist party, quickly\nsaid the Communists weren\u2019t in\nvolved and added \u201cWe liave abso\nlutely no reason to do away with\nGeneral MacArtliur.\"\nTHOSE INVOLVED\nTokayama, former Hem pet i<u\n(thought policei officer who later\nbecame a Kamikaze (suicide) pilot,\nwas known to possess grenades and\npistols, Baker said. He was engag.,\ned for some time fn preliminary\narrangements to \"enlist assistance\nin a plot to kill MucArthur, a head\nquarters statement added, and had\naccumulated 140,000 sen C$9,333; for\nthe purpose.\n\u201cAt one time in his negotiations\nhe attempted to kill, by putting\npoison in his coffee, one cf the plot,\nters because he felt this man\nwould fail,\u201d the announcement said\n'Fortunately, the poison was not\nimmediately fatal. He was taken\nby the Japanese police to an Ameri\ncan hospital, where through crper.\nienced assistance he was revived\nand detailed parts of the plot.\"\nPLOT UNCOVERED\nThe headquarters announcement\nsaid:\n\"A plot ha* been uncovered to\nassassinate the Supreme Command\ner of the Allied Powers aa an In\ncident to the Communist parade\nand mass meeting scheduled for\nMay 1. The leader of the plot is\nHideo Tokayama, who has not yet\nbeen apprehended. Other known\nplotters are still at large, but are\nbeing rounded up.\"\nCol. Harry I. T. Creswell, Mac\nArthur's chief of Civil Intelligence,\nsaid his section \"has no informa\nItion as to Tokayama's politics. In\nfact, no political party was men\ntioned In connections\" with the\n1 case.\nj Creswell said an lnlormant told\nheadquarters of the plot five days\nago. The informant related that\n.five or six persons were involved.\nCreswell said he expected stories\nin the Japanese press about the\nI plot would aid In the apprehensioi\nof Tokayama and the others.\nIdentification of Tokayama was\n[made by Col. Larry Bunker, Mac\nArthur's assistant military tecre\ntary.\nNo extra guards were visible\nI around the MacArthur office to\nday. The announcement stated\n\"The Supreme Commander of the\nAllied Powers has again refused to\npermit any unusual precautions to\njbe taken for the protection of his\nI life.\"\nI\nTIDELANDS BILL\nPASSAGE URGED\nWASHINGTON, April 30.\u2014Pas\nsage of the tidelands bill was urg\ned by the Senate Judiciary com\nmittee yesterday as the \u201conly way\nto set at rest permanently\" a state\nfederal controversy over ownership\nof submerged lands.\nThe committee voted, 8 to 6. last\nTuesday, its approval of the house\npassed bill. Its report, submitted\nby Chairman McCarran <D-Nev>,\nI was made public yesterday,\nj The bill would surrender to the\nstates any federal claim to owner\nship of tidelands and lands be\nneath navigable waters within State\nboundaries, including filled lands.","height":"26644","width":"20852"}}
